  This evaluation provides a complete representation of the       2431 1451
nuclear data needed for transport, damage, heating,               2431 1451
radioactivity, and shielding applications over the incident       2431 1451
neutron energy range from 1.0E-11 to 150 MeV.  The discussion     2431 1451
here is divided into the region below and above 20 MeV.           2431 1451
                                                                  2431 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES < 20 MeV                                2431 1451
                                                                  2431 1451
  Below 20 MeV the evaluation is based completely on the ENDF/B-  2431 1451
VI (Revision 1) evaluation by D. Hetrick, D. Larson, N. Larson,   2431 1451
and C. Y. Fu.                                                     2431 1451
                                                                  2431 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES > 20 MeV                                2431 1451
                                                                  2431 1451
  The ENDF/B-VI Release 2 evaluation extends to 20 MeV and        2431 1451
includes cross sections and energy-angle data for all             2431 1451
significant reactions.  The present evaluation utilizes a more    2431 1451
compact composite reaction spectrum representation above 20 MeV   2431 1451
in order to reduce the length of the file. No essential data for  2431 1451
applications is lost with this representation.                    2431 1451
  The evaluation above 20 MeV utilizes MF=6, MT=5 to represent    2431 1451
all reaction data.  Production cross sections and emission        2431 1451
spectra are given for neutrons, protons, deuterons, tritons,      2431 1451
alpha particles, gamma rays, and all residual nuclides produced   2431 1451
(A>5) in the reaction chains. To summarize, the ENDF sections     2431 1451
with non-zero data above En = 20 MeV are:                         2431 1451
                                                                  2431 1451
  MF=3 MT=  1  Total Cross Section                                2431 1451
       MT=  2  Elastic Scattering Cross Section                   2431 1451
       MT=  3  Nonelastic Cross Section                           2431 1451
       MT=  5  Sum of Binary (n,n') and (n,x) Reactions           2431 1451
                                                                  2431 1451
  MF=4 MT=  2  Elastic Angular Distributions                      2431 1451
                                                                  2431 1451
  MF=6 MT=  5  Production Cross Sections and Energy-Angle         2431 1451
               Distributions for Emission Neutrons, Protons,      2431 1451
               Deuterons, Tritons, and Alphas; and Angle-         2431 1451
               Integrated Spectra for Gamma Rays and Residual     2431 1451
               Nuclei That Are Stable Against Particle Emission   2431 1451
                                                                  2431 1451
  The evaluation is based on nuclear model calculations that      2431 1451
have been benchmarked to experimental data, especially for n +    2431 1451
Cr52 and p + Cr52 reactions [Ch97]. We use the GNASH code system  2431 1451
[Yo92], which utilizes Hauser-Feshbach statistical,               2431 1451
preequilibrium and direct-reaction theories. Spherical optical    2431 1451
model calculations are used to obtain particle transmission       2431 1451
coefficients for the Hauser-Feshbach calculations, as well as     2431 1451
for the elastic neutron angular distributions.                    2431 1451
  Cross sections and spectra for producing individual residual    2431 1451
nuclei are included for reactions. The energy-angle-correlations  2431 1451
for all outgoing particles are based on Kalbach systematics       2431 1451
[Ka88].                                                           2431 1451
  A model was developed to calculate the energy distributions of  2431 1451
all recoil nuclei in the GNASH calculations [Ch96]. The recoil    2431 1451
energy distributions are represented in the laboratory system in  2431 1451
MT=5, MF=6, and are given as isotropic in the lab system. All     2431 1451
other data in MT=5,MF=6 are given in the center-of-mass system.   2431 1451
This method of representation utilizes the LCT=3 option approved  2431 1451
at the November, 1996, CSEWG meeting.                             2431 1451
  Preequilibrium corrections were performed in the course of the  2431 1451
GNASH calculations using the exciton model of Kalbach [Ka77,      2431 1451
Ka85], validated by comparison with calculations using Feshbach,  2431 1451
Kerman, Koonin (FKK) theory [Ch93].  Discrete level data from     2431 1451
nuclear data sheets were matched to continuum level densities     2431 1451
using the formulation of Ignatyuk et al. [Ig75] and pairing and   2431 1451
shell parameters from the Cook [Co67] analysis. Neutron and       2431 1451
charged- particle transmission coefficients were obtained from    2431 1451
the optical potentials, as discussed below.  Gamma-ray            2431 1451
transmission coefficients were calculated using the Kopecky-Uhl   2431 1451
model [Ko90].                                                     2431 1451
                                                                  2431 1451
SOME Cr-SPECIFIC INFORMATION CONCERNING THIS EVALUATION           2431 1451
  The neutron total cross section was evaluated at grid energy    2431 1451
points by using the least-squares code GMA [Po81] taking          2431 1451
account of the new data measured by Dietrich et al. for           2431 1451
natural Cr[Di97].  The results were transformed to the Cr-52      2431 1451
cross section according to A*(2/3) law, i.e., by multiplying a    2431 1451
factor of 0.999305.                                               2431 1451
                                                                  2431 1451
The evaluated total cross section data (present result from 20    2431 1451
to 250 MeV, and ENDF/B-VI value below 20 MeV), s-wave             2431 1451
strength function[Mu81], and elastic scattering angular           2431 1451
distribution data [Ki74, Ol87] were used to obtain the neutron    2431 1451
optical potential parameters.  The parameter estimation was       2431 1451
carried out based on Bayesian approach [Sm91], where ECIS95       2431 1451
code was used for the optical model calculation.  We have         2431 1451
employed the energy dependence of the optical potential           2431 1451
similar to Delaroche's work[De89].  Total of 18 parameters        2431 1451
concerning the central potential were estimated.                  2431 1451
Presently obtained potential was used for the                     2431 1451
calculation of neutron transmission coefficients and DWBA cross   2431 1451
sections in the entire energy region.                             2431 1451
                                                                  2431 1451
For proton channel, a combination of 2 potentials were            2431 1451
used :                                                            2431 1451
below 40 MeV : Becchetti-Greenlees                                2431 1451
above 40 MeV : Madland medium energy potential                    2431 1451
                                                                  2431 1451
The proton reaction cross section and transmission coefficients   2431 1451
below 40 MeV were multiplied by a factor of 0.845 to make the     2431 1451
agreement with the measured proton reaction cross section         2431 1451
[Ca96] better, and also to make the connection to higher energy   2431 1451
values smoothly.                                                  2431 1451
For deuterons, the Lohr-Haeberli global potential was used; for   2431 1451
alpha particles the Moyen potential (MacFadden-Satchler) was      2431 1451
used; and for tritons the Becchetti-Greenlees potential was used. 2431 1451
The He-3 channelwas ignored.                                      2431 1451
